C 1 -- * B
A B has A C. It must always have exactly, one, and can never have none. And there is an upper bound of at most one C.
A C has some Bs. It can have none, and there is no upper bound defined.
When a B is created, its C must be assigned. When a B is deleted, its C is not deleted and its list of Bs is decreased. When a C is deleted, its Bs are not deleted. They are assigned to another C.
